_source.address: 19 Western Avenue, Poole, BH13 7AN
_source.description: T1- yew tree in rear garden next to car port and gym to be dismantled down to ground level. This is a low level tree suppressed by 2 large chestnut trees. Removal will reduce congestion and all more room for the chestnut trees. Owner is happy to replant in a better location. T2 - chestnut tree next to yew and overhanging the car port to have the lowest heavy lateral branch removed. This is a heavy limb overhanging the car port. Due to the length and size, this branch is more prone to snapping out and if it does it will cause significant damage to the property. Removing the branch will remove any risk and help balance the tree. T3 - reduced hole oak in the middle of the rear garden to be removed. This is a poorly formed tree and does not match with the rest of the garden. Removal and replant of a native tree in a better location is recommended. T4 - chestnut tree in the far right corner of the rear garden to have stem overhanging the garden removed. There is clearly significant stress on the main union meaning it may fail with added weight. Removal will leave a single stem tree with no competing stem. It will also remove the risk of failure. T5 - chestnut tree in front garden by pedestrian entrance to have the lowest 2 branches overhanging the road removed. This will crown raise the tree and allow more light to pass under for the newly planted hedge line and smaller trees within the garden. This larger limb is also a heavy lateral limb so removal will remove any chance of limb failure. T6 - lime tree along the front boundary towards the right boarder to be crown lifted on the road side up to 5.2m to match the other lime tree. This will lift the branches up from pavement and road as well as leaving a neat level canopy amongst the line of trees. It will also allow more light to pass under. T7 - neighbours pine tree along the right boarder to have the branch overhanging the applicants property removed. This is an already poorly formed tree and the branch in question is overextended and a poorly formed branch with damage on meaning it's highly likely to fail in high wind now it's left exposed from previous trees being removed. T8 - liquid amber tree in the front garden just in from the right board to have the competing stem crossing between multiple branches removed. This is running on two branches and the stem has minimal growth on so won't affect the shape of the tree.
_source.name: Poole/TP/24/00381/X
